  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How can an international student become a teacher in Scotland?",
  "response": "Becoming a teacher in Scotland as an international student involves several steps. Here's a general guide to help you navigate the process:\n\n1. **Qualifications**:\n   - Ensure that you have a relevant undergraduate degree. In Scotland, teaching requires a degree followed by a teaching qualification.\n   - If your degree is from outside the UK, you may need to have it assessed for equivalency. The Scottish Qualifications Authority (SQA) or UK NARIC (National Recognition Information Centre) can help with this.\n\n2. **Language Proficiency**:\n   - Non-native English speakers need to demonstrate proficiency in English. This might involve taking a recognized language test such as IELTS.\n\n3. **Teacher Training**:\n   - You will need to complete a teacher training program. In Scotland, this typically means obtaining a Postgraduate Diploma in Education (PGDE) or a Bachelor of Education (B.Ed) degree.\n   - Apply to Scottish universities that offer these courses. The application process might involve submitting transcripts, a personal statement, and references.\n\n4. **Visa Requirements**:\n   - Ensure you have the correct visa to study and eventually work in Scotland. You will likely need a Tier 4 (General) student visa to study. After completing your studies, you'll need to switch to a work visa, such as the Tier 2 (General) visa.\n\n5. **Registration with the GTCS**:\n   - Upon completion of your teacher training, you must register with the General Teaching Council for Scotland (GTCS). This involves submitting your qualifications and proof of training. You may also need to pass a background check.\n\n6. **Probationary Year**:\n   - Newly qualified teachers in Scotland must complete a probationary year. This is typically done in a Scottish school and involves monitored teaching practice.\n\n7. **Finding Employment**:\n   - Once registered and having completed your probationary year, you can apply for teaching positions in Scotland. Job vacancies are often advertised on websites like MyJobScotland and individual local authority websites.\n\n8. **Continual Professional Development**:\n   - Engage in ongoing professional development to enhance your skills and career progression. This is encouraged and sometimes required by GTCS.\n\nBy following these steps, you can transition from being an international student to a qualified teacher in Scotland. Remember to regularly check the latest requirements and guidelines from relevant authorities, as policies and procedures can change.",
